  <!-- Advantages -->
  <h2 id="advantages">Advantages</h2>
  <p>
    Centrifuges offer several benefits over conventional heating and settling of crude oil to separate BS&amp;W. The following is a list of the main advantages of crude oil centrifuges.
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>High Throughput:</strong> Centrifuges exert thousands of times the force of gravity, thereby causing instant separation of crude oil from the bottom sediment and water. Traditional settling works under a single force of gravity and takes much longer.</li>
    <li><strong>Compact Size:</strong> Settling tanks have large footprints and therefore require considerable real estate for deployment. Centrifuges are comparatively much smaller to handle the same volume of oil.</li>
    <li><strong>Energy Efficient:</strong> Centrifuges process the crude oil continuously. Therefore, they can use inline heating, which heats up only when the oil is separated. Heater treaters heat thousands of barrels of oil which is colossal energy waste.</li>
    <li><strong>Quick Deployment:</strong> Compared to tank farms with related permitting and land acquisition, the centrifuge can be deployed in a fraction of the time.</li>
    <li><strong>Less Capital Expense:</strong> Considering the cost of land, tankage, permits, and disposal facilities, the cost of heating and settling is far greater than that of a centrifuge system.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduced Oil Losses:</strong> It is possible to produce oil with less than 1% BS&amp;W with a centrifuge system with minimal losses. A considerable amount of oil is lost in drained bottoms to achieve similar quality oil.</li>
    <li><strong>Better Quality Oil:</strong> The high g-force exerted by centrifuges leads to a much higher quality of crude oil when compared to oil produced by simple gravity settling.</li>
    <li><strong>Reduced Disposal Costs:</strong> A centrifuge-produced dry sludge cake (reduced disposal volume) reduces disposal costs. Conventional tank bottoms contain higher amounts of oil and water, leading to larger disposal volumes.</li>
  </ul>

